    <h3 class="landmark heading" id="work">Chapter Text</h3>
    <p>Â </p><p>The path that leads him into the woods is paved in smooth stone, dark like the earth after rain. Link walks with the clink of golden armour and there is nobody around to hear it. Folk in these parts know better than to follow roads that stay pretty without being tended. Bandits swarm in the dusty by-lanes, but better to have coin stolen and barns raided than to chance the gaping maw of the trees.</p><p>Â </p><p>People have mercy. Forests donâ€™t.</p><p>Â </p><p>He walks into the mist. The road winds around in circles, then peters out, slowly, like a river reaching the sea. His boots sink into grass that brushes his knees. He can feel eyes on his spine.</p><p>Â </p><p>He takes a deep breath and releases it.</p><p>Â </p><p>He was born here. But he does not belong here. He knows the feeling of the sun through the trees better than he knows his name, or his face, or the sword calluses on his palm, but the wood is perilous to him still.</p><p>Â </p><p>The easy way leads deeper, to the heart, the places he cannot find again and will lose himself trying. And he is here only for a shortcut. Time is different in the woods. Slower. Thicker. So he must take the harder way, through the nettles and the thorns.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>If all goes well, he will pass without disturbing anything that sleeps here, and will emerge from the thickets behind Castle Town at the other end of the countryâ€”how soon, he canâ€™t tell. No more than a kokiri hour, as the children used to say, even though he canâ€™t remember how long the kokiri hour was.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œBoything,â€ something whispers to him. He sighs.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYes, kid?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>The puppet looks at him, wide-eyed. â€œBoything,â€ it says again, like itâ€™s testing the word out. It doesnâ€™t know his name. Heâ€™s not young and innocent enough to give it. Better to be nameless.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYes?â€ he answers, though itâ€™s been decades since anybody called him a boy. He used to be one, he thinks. Briefly. In between being a child and a monster.</p><p>Â </p><p>The puppetâ€™s finger twitches as he sets down the pack full of masks and lets his sword fall to rest beneath a tree. A dedicated finger of wind is winding carefully through the trees. He tips his head and lets it cool his skin.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œThereâ€™s people in the woods,â€ the puppet tells him, with insects instead of pupils caught in the amber eyes of its wooden face. The one in the left eye looks like some sort of wasp, angry and black and long extinct. All the kids are older than ancient. Time moves differently in the woods.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œPeople?â€ he repeats. Another puppet crawls out of the shrubbery, joints sliding in opposition to his own. â€œCanâ€™t you chase them out of the woods?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWe think you should do it,â€ the second kid confides. â€œThese ones are different.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYouâ€™re being interrupted at a game,â€ he translates.</p><p>Â </p><p>Neither kid will meet his eyes, which all but confirms it. A third puppet suddenly touches the small of his back and he catches himself from leaping a foot into the air. â€œBoything, youâ€™re gold,â€ it says wonderingly.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œItâ€™s armour,â€ he replies patiently, and brushes the thingâ€™s wooden hands off his belt, retrieving the tiny hunting knife that has been quietly taken from him. The puppet lets him take it, hands placid and easy to manoeuvre, like a childâ€™s. â€œFor protection.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWe can do protection,â€ the kids offer. â€œWithout gold, even.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œThatâ€™s kind,â€ he tells them, politely, â€œbut I like my armour.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Protection to a skull kid is wood and mist and eternity. He cannot lose himself now. Sheâ€™s waiting for him at home, a lanturn burning in the window.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOkay,â€ he says. â€œIâ€™ll lead them out.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOut, in,â€ the first kid says idly. â€œDoesnâ€™t matter. Make them go.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOkay,â€ he says again. Thereâ€™s nothing else he can say.</p><p>Â </p><p>If the kids could move their faces, he thinks they would smile. As it is, laughter bubbles from their wooden throats. The grins carved into their faces seem a little more sincere. â€œYouâ€™re welcome to join the game,â€ one of them burbles instead of thanks. The forest does not say thanks.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOnce theyâ€™re gone?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOnce theyâ€™re gone!â€ the kids agree, and run in their jerky, shuddering way under the low-hanging branch of a shadowy tree, into fog so white he cannot see them go. He buckles his pack and picks up his sword. The forest must not be allowed to steal them.</p><p>Â </p><p>He will have to make a detour on his shortcut. No matter. Time moves differently in the woods. It slips and slides aroundâ€”changes faces in the unblinking stare of an amber eye, in the wind that canâ€™t decide which direction to blow from, the compass that spins never ending. Heâ€™ll still be early if he needs to.</p><p><br />
