    <p>Â </p><p>On the first night of their new adventure, before they meet the god, the eight of them build a fire in the woods. It burns hot and bright in the relentless fog. The stars are shrouded beyond reach; the air still, the trees calm. They are adrift in history.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œHas anyone ever met giant llama people?â€ Wild asks, flames casting a bronze shadow across the burn scars on his face.</p><p>Â </p><p>Warriors straightens slightly, listening as everyone around the circle dissents with varying degrees of incredulity. The man with the blue cap and peach-pink bangs, fingers ringed with goldâ€”the one who immediately called him a prick when Warriors introduced himself as a captain in the Queenâ€™s Armyâ€”quirks a crooked eyebrow, as if to say, <em> giant llama people? Can you believe it? </em></p><p>Â </p><p>Warriors digs his fingernails into his scarred palm. He canâ€™t. Maybe the War was supposed to teach him, and maybe he should be used to stumbling into myths and fairytales, into the past, but he has never been so violently lost before. The fairytales have always come to <em> him, </em>to where he had battalions and generals and marching orders. There have always been expectations.</p><p>Â </p><p>Now they have no map and no leader and no common Queen to unite them. The sailor is younger, barely more than a preteen, and the masked child is nowhere to be found. The loss is a dull, relentless ache.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œNobody?â€ Wild sighs, and flops off his log to land sprawled across the grass. Twilight pokes him with one booted foot and he sticks out his tongue in lazy retaliation.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œCub, why would weâ€™ve seen giantâ€”whatsit?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œLlama,â€ says Wind helpfully.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œLlama people?â€ Twilight finishes.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI donâ€™t know,â€ says Wild. The fire sputters. â€œThere was a Zonai Kingdom, for a while, instead of Hyrule. Iâ€™m trying to figure out where I am on the timeline.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Silenc