e boy shakes his head. What was his name? Why canâ€™t Warriors remember? â€œHe did,â€ he insists. â€œFor so long that we forgot to watch for him in the night.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Legend suddenly looks like a man drowning. The boy reaches out, fingers light, as if to touch a monument.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Warriors watches them. The boyâ€™s hand curls into Legendâ€™s fingers and the blue-capped hero shudders soundlessly. What does it feel like to hold history in the palm of your hand? What does it feel like to hold the future?Â </p><p>Â </p><p>The silence stretches on, and neither of them let go.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYou must live in an era after mine,â€ Twilight says to Wild. The moment shatters. The nameless boy retreats. â€œThat slate is like no technology Iâ€™ve ever seen before.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWhoâ€™s before me, then?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI know whoâ€™s before me,â€ Wind offers. Warriors glances at him briefly.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>It was strange having to introduce himself to his own brother. He observes from a careful distance the baby fat in Windâ€™s cheeks, seeing the places where it will thin and where the bone structure of his jawline will emerge.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWho?â€ Sky asks.</p><p>Â </p><p>Wind leans forward, ushering them closer, as if heâ€™s about to tell a secret. Warriors leans in despite himself. The kid had always been charismatic; a storyteller. The memories of his brother are plastered on top of this foreign young version despite all efforts to redirect his thinking. A living ghost, who gets pissed off more often than amused and whose blond hair is curlier than Warriors ever saw it.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œThe Hero of Time,â€ the sailor says. His voice comes like a breath of wind. They collectively shiver. The Hero of Time is a boogeyman; a wraith. Something that lurks around the edges of every story.</p><p>Â </p><p>Mist envelopes them. Warriors glances back at the pale trees, but they are alone.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI met his ghost, once,â€ Twilight says. â€