 And Wildâ€™s technology is so complex.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Wind snorts. â€œIt canâ€™t be <em> that </em> advanced,â€ he says. â€œIn my time, the old pirates say thereâ€™s a land to the west where the people ride around in machines on rails.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWhat about after Wild and before Sky?â€ Twilight offers.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYeah, that could make sense,â€ Wild agrees. â€œA lot of our oral history was destroyed whenâ€¦ well, we still have records, but itâ€™s not uncommon to find small settlements that are mostly cut off from the wider world.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOkay.â€ Four tosses the stick into the fire and leans over his drawing. â€œThere. Thatâ€™s all eight of us.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œAnd the Hero of Time,â€ Twilight points out. The fire crackles. â€œHeâ€™s at the top. The beginning of the world.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œHe must have split the timelines,â€ Legend murmurs. Hyrule drifts closer, peering over his shoulder.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI thought you said a mortal couldnâ€™t do that,â€ Sky says.</p><p>Â </p><p>Impaâ€™s eyes, like carnelians. <em> They say that time was broken, long ago. </em></p><p>Â </p><p>â€œMaybe I was wrong,â€ Warriors says aloud. â€œOrâ€¦ maybe I wasnâ€™t.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Beside the fire, Wind shivers.</p><p>Â </p><p>He has to say something.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œIn the war,â€ Warriors starts, watching them turn towards him like the battlefield crows to carrion; like men to the blade that brings their deaths: â€œI met other heroes from other times. One of them was a child.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYou let a child fight in a <em> war?â€ </em>Legend snaps.</p><p>Â </p><p>Twilightâ€™s brow creases.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI had no choice,â€ Warriors says, and begins to laugh. â€œHe was more powerful than I was and didnâ€™t take no for an answer. I sent him away, I gave him errands, I assigned soldiers to watch him. He slipped them all. On the battlefieldâ€¦â€</p><p>Â </p><p>He swallows.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œHe carried masks,â€ he continues, forcing the words out. â€œThe masksâ€¦ changed him. Allowed him to take the shape of other creatures.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Wild makes a curious noise.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOne was more powerful than the rest. A hylian faceâ€”or, it <em> looked </em>hylian. When he wore itâ€¦ he was taller than two men stacked. There were coloured tattoos on his face. His skin wasâ€¦ leeched of colour. Eyes went white.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Warriors hides his shaking hands in his scarf. Heâ€™d slipped on a corpse and fallen. A moblin had decided to take the opportunity to skewer him. It hadnâ€™t been the first time heâ€™d known with cold, detached clarity that he was about to die, but it had been one of the worst.</p><p>Â </p><p>Then the silver double helix had come down like a bolt of lightning on the moblin, splitting apart the bone of its skull easier than Warriors shelled peanuts. The giant had tilted his head and <em> looked </em>at him cowering in the mud. Eyes blank. Eerily silent. He hadnâ€™t known it was the child, underneath, back then. Heâ€™d thought it was some sort of angel. The giant stood alone on the battlefield, like a pillar in the grey rain, while soldiers scrambled for their swords.</p><p>Â </p><p><em> Stand down, </em> Warriors had managed through a broken rib, before they carried him away. <em> Heâ€™s an ally. </em></p><p>Â </p><p>â€œThe child was a hero in his own right.â€ He clears his throat. â€œBut the maskâ€¦ he didnâ€™t like to talk about it. He wouldnâ€™t tell me where it came from or how he got a hold on it.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œBut you think you know?â€ Legend says, eyes glittering. He leans in closer, eyebrows furrowed.</p><p>Â </p><p>Warriors swallows. â€œI think I do,â€ he agrees. â€œThe child mentioned a town of clocks, once, when he was half-asleep. And he used to flinch when Impa spoke of the splitting of the timelineâ€”he was very sensitive to discussions of history. He told me the mask was modelled from the body of a great warrior.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYou think it was modelled