</p><p>It is not a heroâ€™s right to question the gods.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Linkâ€”Time, nowâ€”emerges from the portal, and shakes off the eddies of thick, buzzing energy that cling to his armour. He can taste Hyliaâ€™s brand of divinity on the back of his tongue. Itâ€™s icy and sweet and familiar. He almost feels the phantom sensation of the ocarina in his palms.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>The strange men are waiting for him on the other side. If they can be called men<em> . </em></p><p>Â </p><p>It had been a shock, at first, to hear them introduce themselves. <em> Iâ€™m known as Warriors, </em> the creature holding out his hand in hylian greeting fashion had said. <em> This is Windâ€¦ </em>His skin was warm. It was strange. Time has never been allowed to touch a god before. What a sight they had made in the Lost Woods, all eight of them surrounded by great coils of magic, pulsing through them and around them. It had taken all he had not to clam up like a child when they said he was welcome in their group.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>A man walking among immortals. Malon is not going to <em> believe </em>this.</p><p>Â </p><p>The one he shook hands with is representative of warriors. Fitting, then, that he wears a similar-looking pauldron as the young captain from Timeâ€™s childhood, whose face and voice is now lost to his fading memory. The others range from gleeful to surly, but each of them have a facade of youth. The Wind has taken the shape of a <em> boy, </em>for Nayruâ€™s sake: as playful and impulsive as the element he is made of. It is absurd to realise Time appears to be the eldest of them.</p><p>Â </p><p>Time squints into the afternoon sun and the battlements around. Theyâ€™ve arrived in a courtyard, paved with diamonds. The shapes teaseâ€¦ Heâ€™s been to this place, long ago. Itâ€™s familiar.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œOoh, this is Warriorsâ€™ <em> least </em>favourite Hyrule,â€ the child-shaped god says cheerfully.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œIs not,â€ Warriors grumbles. â€œThatâ€™d make me a t