>â€œAnd how do you <em> know that?â€ </em></p><p>Â </p><p>â€œSettle down,â€ Time says, like heâ€™s dreaming, like heâ€™s going to wake up into a life where the bones of his brothers havenâ€™t been lost in the dirt under his feet forâ€”it must be centuries. Centuries.</p><p>Â </p><p>He finds in that single moment he never really believed they could have died.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œCanâ€™t we have just a minute to sit down?â€ Sky puffs. â€œWarriorsâ€™ guards just chased us down half the citadel.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>They had always been soâ€”so <em> real. </em> In the council chambers he half-expected them to come waltzing in unannounced. In the kitchen at home, rolling out dough, he thinks of them fondly; blond hair in the marketplace turns his head, stops his heart. He knew better than to think he would find them again but still he hoped. As with every piece of his past. He is no good at accepting lost thingsâ€”maybe, he has always dared to think. Maybe. Malon keeps plates of sugar water on the stiles for his sake. On the windowsills there are candle-stubs in jars, ever-burning. <em> Weâ€™re here, Iâ€™m here, youâ€™re home.Â  </em></p><p>Â </p><p>His brothers will never find him.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œSmell,â€ Wild says. <em> â€œSmell.â€ </em></p><p>Â </p><p>Time inhales and the wood-sweet smell of the Lost Woods hits him like a boulder to the skull. This new grief slips away out of reach, out of words. It leaves a shadow in its wake. He knows more than feels that his eyes have gone wild. Fairy eyes, Malon calls them, whenever the wind carries an unexpected note of spring, or when the dusk creeps upon him unawares while heâ€™s working. Itâ€™s a rush.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>The Lost Woods look different. Something in the colour of the trees, the shape of the wind as it curls around them, slow and thick. Leaves rustle like the feathers of a slumbering beast. The grass is longer but thinner, wetter like this new world is suspended in a state of sunshowers and dew. Which god is responsib