>Â </p><p>He steps off the not-path. It is trickery, nothing more. The dewy grass is no safer than the nettles. Both are pretending to be something they are not. He is practised in the art of keeping himself when the forest tries to lure him.</p><p>Â </p><p>There are eyes on his spine.</p><p>Â </p><p>As he walks, a soft whistle falls from his lips, but no kids appear at his waist and from behind. The chattering and gurgling and pinching he is hoping for never comes. There are no Skull Kids in this Lost Woods, then. No guardians. Where did they go? All the kids are older than ancient. They would not have given up so easily.</p><p>Â </p><p>The Lost Woods are closed to them.</p><p><br />â€œTime?â€ someone asks. â€œWhy have we stopped?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œAre you following me?â€ he asks, bizarrely touched. The gods shrug almost audibly.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWe didnâ€™t have a better plan,â€ the god of legends says, so vulnerable in his words. So mortal. Magic is a troublemaker; itâ€™s a storytellerâ€™s job to exaggerate, to lie nicely. â€œYou seem like you know what youâ€™re doing.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Time almost chuckles. If only they knew. If they had been trying to find a token mortal who understood mortal life, he was a terrible stroke of luck for them. Instead he whistles again, sharper, more insistent, a demand rather than a greeting, and the wood responds. Fog leaps up around their feet and washes them into a deep white storm. And there are lights, in the fog, glowing lights, almost-fairies but not quite. A mimicry. A lure. The wind curls around his wrist as if to steal his hand away. Itâ€™s made of laughter, he realises. Tinkling, gurgling laughter. Familiar, still, all these years later.</p><p>Â </p><p><em> We know you, </em>says the fog and the wind.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>He does not speak the languages of weather, but he listens. He finds he knows them back.</p><p>Â </p><p><em> We know you, we know youâ€¦ </em> the kids whisper. How bored they must have become, to she