</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œEnough riddles,â€ he does not say, because the kids have always loved riddles. â€œPlease,â€ another word discarded. People have mercy. Forests donâ€™t. â€œAsk my father,â€ is what he settles for, though thereâ€™s a lump in his throat. The gods are curling around in their ring of handholding to listen to him.Â </p><p>Â </p><p><em> The fathertree is soft at the root, </em>says the mist.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œSo take me to him,â€ Time barters. And like an ocean parting, the forest does.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>The mist clears for them; the trees lift their creeping boughs and close their toothy maws and shift aside like illusions collapsing. A path appears like an arrow shot from a bow. Time grasps the young hand of the wind god, another illusion, and tugs them all into the woods. The kid laughs as they hurry, delighted, and for a moment the memory of his older brother strikes him through the heart. The sailor used to laugh in the exact same way. Like he was half in awe of being alive.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>No longer.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWho is it?â€ someone calls, as they wind along the path in single file, hands overlapping. â€œWho are we going to see?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI think I can guess,â€ laughs the wind. His hand is warm. Itâ€™s too much. â€œA wise old guardian. Heart of the forest.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Time makes a sound. â€œHe is not the heart,â€ he says. â€œOr else we would not be permitted entry.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œExplain,â€ Legend says, short.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œHe grows around the heart,â€ Time says, because it is folly to deny a god, and folly to tell one theyâ€™re wrong. Itâ€™s only a lie in the same way it would be to say that Wind is a child. His father is not called <em>Great </em>without reason, and although the forest has never changedâ€”had never changedâ€”the trees are not without mischief. They might be allowed an audience with one side of his father, but that would not mean they would find the heart. Secret places, hidden places, other sides w