</p><p>â€œHello, father.â€Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Eyelashes pressed into his cheeks, forehead smooth, the god touches the tree like a homecoming. From all around the clearing, the creatures Wild described as koroks emerge as if they were called. Like flowers to the sun they turn to him. Their little propellers spin silently. Hyrule gathers the armful of blue star-shaped flowers Wild gives him, watchful. Wary.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œMy son,â€ comes the reply. So it is true. Timeâ€™s father is a <em> tree. </em>How does it work? How is a god born of a plant? Did he crawl out of the bushes as a baby, like Wild climbing sopping wet from the Shrine? No. That was a rebirth, from how he tells it. Like Hyrule himself, then, who only remembers the road. Like Time shed his branches one day and stepped out of the soil.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI never thought Iâ€™d see you again,â€ the god says again. He leans closer. Hyrule sees Wind squeeze his hand a little, for comfort. Warriorsâ€™ eyebrows move a little.</p><p>Â </p><p>The tree laughs. â€œYou could have tried,â€ it says.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Time shakes his head. â€œNoâ€”Iâ€”the kokiri canâ€™t leave the lost woods. Weâ€™reâ€”weâ€™re not allowed. I wasnâ€™t supposed to.â€ He takes a breath, and then another, and then continues, quieter. â€œI left. I wasnâ€™t swallowed by the lost woods. Iâ€”â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œKokiri,â€ Wild hisses at Hyrule. â€œThatâ€™s different. I know <em> korok, </em>butâ€”â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œKokiri,â€ Hyrule echoes.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œThe ultimate test of belonging,â€ Time admits. â€œI did not want to be proven wrong.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYou have not been stolen yet,â€ the tree says evenly. â€œDoes that not answer your question?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œI havenâ€™t gone deep enough,â€ Time responds. He shakes his head. â€œI havenâ€™t gone deep enough.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>The tree rumbles. Hyrule tenses a little. Itâ€™sâ€”he canâ€™t help it. This Great Deku Tree is <em> huge. </em>Beyond the green canopy, there is another higher canopy, a pink one, not made from leaves but great trailing blossoms. Honey-sweet, big enough to contain the entire clearing underneath it. The tree is what Hyrule has been smelling the entire time, he realises. Notes of it in the wind and the fog. Thick enough now at the epicentre that he feels like heâ€™s floating.</p><p>Â </p><p>Wild darts away. Hyrule grips his flowers and follows, under the mammoth tree-roots, through the grass. Thereâ€™s a path, a sort of tunnel, more flowers, a few decorated wood-pots. They look a little like huge, hollowed-out nuts, but that would be ridiculous. Tree-nuts donâ€™t grow big enough for Hyrule to put his boots in.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Trees donâ€™t grow big enough to have <em> furniture </em> inside them <em> . </em></p><p>Â </p><p>â€œDo you know what he was talking about?â€ Hyrule prompts, nudging Wild.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Wild scowls. â€œWhat does it mean?â€ he asks the korok on the other side of the cookpot, which isÂ  bubbling away like it was waiting for them. Hyrule eyes the leaf-bed in an alcove curiously. Is that for Wild? Time? All of them? Or is this place like the visitorâ€™s suite of the woods? Time told them all it wasnâ€™t the heartâ€”so what was it?</p><p>Â </p><p>Wild flicks his tongue, then makes an attempt at curling it into the shape of the word Time had dropped like well-worn velvet. â€œ<em> Kokiri?â€ </em></p><p>Â </p><p>The korok burbles.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œKokiri?â€ Wild tries again. Hyrule passes him a flower and gives it his own take.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œ<em> Kokiri,â€ </em>he says, with a little bit of fairy in the word.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œMe,â€ says the korok.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œNot korok, <em> kokiri.â€ </em></p><p>Â </p><p>â€œMe!â€ says the korok again. Then it laughs. â€œYa-ha-ha-ha!â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œIf youâ€™re kokiri,â€ Hyrule says, giving Wild another flower. â€œWhereâ€™s your leaf-clothes? And your hat? And your fairy?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYou know what a kokiri is,â€ Wild says bluntly.Â </p><p>