rule thrashes around and tries to buck him off uselessly. Heâ€™s laughing so hard his stomach hurts<em> .Â  </em></p><p>Â </p><p>â€œIâ€™m gonnaâ€”Iâ€™mâ€”Iâ€™m gonna <em> bite you,â€ </em>he gasps out, still writhing.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œYou wouldnâ€™t,â€ Twilight starts to say with far too much confidence, before Hyrule latches on to his forearm. He yelps like a startled dog and flings Hyrule back across the grass.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Â â€œItâ€™s my secret weapon,â€ Hyrule gasps, laughter fading, and bares his teeth.</p><p>Â </p><p>Twilight bares his teeth right back. Theyâ€™re much pointier.Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWhat do you think of him?â€Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œThe Great Deku Tree?â€ Twilight asks, thrown by the change in conversation.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œTime, of course.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Twilightâ€™s eyes flick to the side, and up, to where Wind is dangling his little boots off the side of the root and kicking them around idly. The god himselfâ€”both of them, because the Great Deku Tree must be divine or at least immortal, to be this powerful, to have lasted this longâ€”are talking in low voices. Twilightâ€™s jaw tightens, and he starts putting his socks back on. â€œKidâ€™s taken a shine to him.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œWhat about you?â€ Hyrule presses.</p><p>Â </p><p>Twilight flicks his sock out to get the grass off it and doesnâ€™t answer. Hyrule wrinkles his nose.</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œIf Ordona weren't already keeping an eye on me, I'd pray to him,â€ he eventually says, gruff. â€œBetween her and the Light Spirits, I'd say my ass is covered.â€Â </p><p>Â </p><p>â€œHe seems like a good man,â€ Hyrule returns. He blinks. â€œAre gods also men? A good deity? Kind, at least. Kinder than I might've thought. I'm sure a lot of people do pray to him.â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œMaybe you should start,â€ Twilight says, uncharacteristically distant. â€œHasn't there ever been nothing you wanted to change?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>â€œSurely even a god can't fix the past?â€</p><p>Â </p><p>Twilight shrugs. â€œT